Administrative_areas: Sal (Terra Boa); Boa Vista (Rª de Sta Isabel, Bofareira, Estância de Baixo, João Galego, Cabeça dos Tarafes, Fundo Figueira, Rabil); Maio (Laje Branca- Cascabulho, Figueira Horta- Rª Chico Vaz, Rª Lagoa). São Vicente (Rª  Vinha, Rª Madeiral, Rª Calhau, Rª
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed agriculture is marginal. Horticultural production hydroponic greenhouse is in full expansion.Rainfed cultivation of maize, common beans, date palms, watermelon, coconut, and melon. Horticultural production on a small scale.Rainfed maize, common beans. Water distribution not even.Potential for irrigated cultivation of onions and roots and tubers.The pluvial agriculture is limited. Irrigation from wells situated in valleys. Pumping with wind energy from shallow well. Very high salinity especially at the end of season (May - July). The majority of horticultural crops (lettuce, beetroot, coriander, cabbage,..) are cultivated with the dripper irrigation. Very strong winds. Use of wind breaks and cultivation in insect-proof greenhouses (tomato, lettuce, cabbage,..).

Administrative_areas: S. Nicolau (Fajã, Rª das Pratas-Fragata, Rª Brava, Caleijão, Queimadas, Juncalinho, Água das Patas)S. Antão: Porto Novo (Rª da Cruz, Alto Mira, Martiene, Lagedos, Rª Fria, Rª dos Bodes, Casa de Meio) - Sud et Ouest; Fogo: S. Filipe (Achada Malva, Patim, F
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed cultivation in maize and common beans. Pluvial land (35 ha) converted to irrigated areas (Faja Galery). Irrigated crops on wind-protected valleys with micro-climate that is favourable for sugar cane and fruit production. Fruits (mango) on the sides of the valleys with complementary irrigation. High water deficit in some zones according to season. Gravitational irrigation with water from streams and wells. Moderate micro-climate in hot humid season (July - Oct.) conducive for fruit and vegetable production (potato, cabbage, sweetpotato, citrus and mango). Little or no pests with the exception of millipedes. Insufficient rainfall. Irrigation of small farms with water bored more than 100 m deep on slopes. Water pumping from the sea level with several intermediate stations. Potential for roots and tuber production, pineapple, pawpaw and horticultural crops with micro-irrigation. Very high price of water.

Administrative_areas: Brava: (Vila, Covoada, N. Sra do Monte, Campo Baixo, Sorno, Ferreiros); S. Antão: Ribeira Grande (Rª Grande, Rª da Torre, Rª de garça); Paul (Rª de Paul, Campo, Chã d'Igreja) - Nord; Fogo: (Mosteiros - Pai António, Igreja).
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed cultivation is developed, especially with maize/common beans, manioc, sweet potato and mango. Potential zone for horticulture (especially temperate crops). Sugar cane is the most cultivated. This limit the cultivation of other crops (cabbage, potato, onion, carrot, cassava, potato). Irrigation is mostly gravitational from water sources. Presence of pests, especially millipedes. Rainfed production of maize/beans, cassava, sweet potato and mango.

Administrative_areas: São Vicente (Monte Verde); S. Nicolau (Monte Gordo, Fajã de Riba); S. Antão (Cova, Corda, Covão, Fundão, Pintão, Lombo Branco, Figueiral, Pico da Cruz, Santa Isabel,..) - Centre; Fogo: Mosteiros (Monte Velha, Rª do Iheu, Atalaia Campanas, Galinheiro) - No
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed cultivation of some food crops (maize, common beans, roots and tubers, groundnuts and some vegetables (2 cropping season/year). In the altitude there is cultivation of maize/common beans, sweetpotato, and temperate fruits (apple, peach, grape, quince). Rainfed cultivation at the altitude of 600-700 m crops such as maize/common beans, tubers, coffee. Rainfed cultivation of maize, common beans, cucurbits, roots and tubers predominate. The mixed system (pluvial/irrigated is very developed in this zone. There are pre-rainfed crops such as cabbage, potato, lettuce, etc) and some experience with harvesting surface  waters and clouds (S. malagueta).

Sugar cane is the most cultivated. This limit the cultivation of other crops (cabbage, potato, onion, carrot, cassava, potato). Irrigation is mostly gravitational from water sources. Presence of pests, especially millipedes. Rainfed production of maize/beans, cassava, sweet potato and mango.

Administrative_areas: São Vicente (Monte Verde); S. Nicolau (Monte Gordo, Fajã de Riba); S. Antão (Cova, Corda, Covão, Fundão, Pintão, Lombo Branco, Figueiral, Pico da Cruz, Santa Isabel,..) - Centre; Fogo: Mosteiros (Monte Velha, Rª do Iheu, Atalaia Campanas, Galinheiro) - No
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed cultivation of some food crops (maize, common beans, roots and tubers, groundnuts and some vegetables (2 cropping season/year). In the altitude there is cultivation of maize/common beans, sweetpotato, and temperate fruits (apple, peach, grape, quince). Rainfed cultivation at the altitude of 600-700 m crops such as maize/common beans, tubers, coffee. Rainfed cultivation of maize, common beans, cucurbits, roots and tubers predominate. The mixed system (pluvial/irrigated is very developed in this zone. There are pre-rainfed crops such as cabbage, potato, lettuce, etc) and some experience with harvesting surface  waters and clouds (S. malagueta).

Sugar cane is the most cultivated. This limit the cultivation of other crops (cabbage, potato, onion, carrot, cassava, potato). Irrigation is mostly gravitational from water sources. Presence of pests, especially millipedes. Rainfed production of maize/beans, cassava, sweet potato and mango.

Administrative_areas: São Vicente (Monte Verde); S. Nicolau (Monte Gordo, Fajã de Riba); S. Antão (Cova, Corda, Covão, Fundão, Pintão, Lombo Branco, Figueiral, Pico da Cruz, Santa Isabel,..) - Centre; Fogo: Mosteiros (Monte Velha, Rª do Iheu, Atalaia Campanas, Galinheiro) - No
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed cultivation of some food crops (maize, common beans, roots and tubers, groundnuts and some vegetables (2 cropping season/year). In the altitude there is cultivation of maize/common beans, sweetpotato, and temperate fruits (apple, peach, grape, quince). Rainfed cultivation at the altitude of 600-700 m crops such as maize/common beans, tubers, coffee. Rainfed cultivation of maize, common beans, cucurbits, roots and tubers predominate. The mixed system (pluvial/irrigated is very developed in this zone. There are pre-rainfed crops such as cabbage, potato, lettuce, etc) and some experience with harvesting surface  waters and clouds (S. malagueta).

Administrative_areas: Covers the majority of the national territory, between 5° and 9° N and the towns of Bouar (Nana Mambéré), Bossembélé (Ombella M'Poko), Bozoum (Ouham Péndé), Bossangoa (Ouham), Kaga Bandoro (Nana Gribizi), Sibut (Kémo), Bambari (Ouaka), Ndélé south, Bria (
Agricultural_practices: Fallowing is practised with bush burning. In some areas the density of trees and shrubs limits deep ploughing. Animal traction is used in the savannah and cotton zones for ploughing and transportation. The cropping calendar depends on rainfall regime. Fertilizers are not used in food crop cultivation. The soil is placed on fallow for more than 4 years.

Agricultural_practices: Fallowing is practised with bush burning. In the cotton areas, some farmers use animal traction, but the rest of the system is manual. The cultural calendar depends on rainfall regime. Fertilizers are not applied on food crops. The soil is placed on fallow for a long period for natural regeneration.

Administrative_areas: Dodoma: Dodoma rural, Kondoa, Chamwino, Mpwapwa, Manyoni, and Bahi.Singida Singida rural, and Iramba. Manyara: Babati, Hanang and Mbulu. Mbeya: Chunya. Arusha: Karatu. Shinyanga: Bukombe, Kahama, Maswa, Shinyanga rural and Meatu. Tabora: Sikonge, Igunga,
Agricultural_practices: Main crops: sorghum, millets, groundnuts, sunflower, sweet potato, cassava, maize (early maturing and medium term), pigeon pea, hyacinth bean, passion fruit, cotton, sisal, castor, simsim, tea, coffee, Irish potatoes, common beans, grasses and legumes for livestock, grapes, rice, vegetables. Main farming/cropping system: sorghum/bulrush/millet/ Livestock/ maize/ bulrush millet/ cotton/ livestock. Other crops are: oil seeds and rice. Cotton/maize (other crops involved: sweet potato, sorghum and groundnut). Pastoralist/agropastoralist (with shifting cultivation of sorghum). Irrigation: traditional schemes operating with upgraded ones e.g. Lumuma. Major pests: any worms, locusts, rodents, large grain borer. Sources of seed: own saved and from stockists. Fertilizers recommended but used in small quantities.

Agricultural_practices: Main crops: cassava, simsim, finger millet, sorghum, cow pea, pigeon pea, pine apple, sweet potato, soybean, groundnut, passion fruit, finger millet, mango, cashew, cotton, mango, coconut, sisal, jatropha, citrus cloves, rubber, oil palm and sugar cane. Early maturing maize varieties grown in soils with high moisture storing capacity. Crop rotations: maize/beans/maize. Beans -maize/sorghum-cassava. tomato/maize/tomato. Main farming/cropping system: cashew/coconut/cassava; coconut/citrus/maize/cassava/sweet potato. Some shifting cultivation is still practiced. Rice/sugar system found in alluvial river valley (Rufiji, Kilombero river valleys, Morogoro, Mvomero and Pangani. Wet rice and irrigation system at river valleys and alluvial plains. Irrigation: The sugar cane plantations have modern irrigation facilities. Source of seed: mainly from informal system-own saved, gift or exchange or purchased from local market. The system provides about 90% of seeds. Formal system from stockist and provide about 10% of seed source. Fertilizer although recommended are used in small quantities. Major pests: insect pests (army worms, locust), birds (Quellea Quellea), rodents.

Various tropical grasses and legumes for animal fodder. Main farming/cropping system: maize/legumes; maize/legume/horticulture; maize/legume/livestock or legume/sorghum/livestock; banana/coffee/horticulture; banana/coffee/horticulture/livestock. Irrigation: mainly traditional but upscaled in vegetables and rice growing areas. Source of seed: informal and formal. Temperate seeds such as carrot. Cabbages are imported. Major pests: insects: armyworms, locust; birds (Quellea Quellea); rodents.

Various tropical grasses and legumes for animal fodder. Main farming/cropping system: maize/legumes; maize/legume/horticulture; maize/legume/livestock or legume/sorghum/livestock; banana/coffee/horticulture; banana/coffee/horticulture/livestock. Agroecological_zones: Rukwa - Ruaha Rift Zone - Alluvial Flats
Administrative_areas: Mbeya: Mbeya rural, Mbozi and Mbarali. Rukwa: Mpanda, Nkasi and Sumbawanga. Kigoma: Kigoma rural. Dodoma: Chamwino, Mpwapwa.
Agricultural_practices: Main crops: sorghum, pigeon pea, hyacinth bean, banana, citrus, passion fruit, simsim, cotton, rice, millets, grape, groundnut, early and medium term maturing maize, sweet potato, sunflower, castor. Farming /cropping systems: wet rice and irrigated system. Pastoralist and Agropastoralist, sorghum/ bulrush millet/ livestock (or maize, rice). Cotton/maize (other crops: maize, sorghum, sweet potato and groundnut). Irrigation schemes: both traditional and modern are operating e.g. Mbarari Rice Irrigation Scheme. Sources of seed: own saved, from stockists and on farm produced. Farmers use both organic and artificial fertilizers but not up to the recommended rates. Local varieties. Maize, sorghum.

Administrative_areas: Upper Nile, Unity, Buhayrat, Bahr el-Ghazal & Warap, Eastern Equatoria & Jongli, while the Western Equatoria & Bahr el-Jble are characterized by rocks and stony plains
Agricultural_practices: Due to the rich forests - this zone is characterized by the existence of wild-game. Sorghum, sesame, groundnut, cassava, rice, coffee, tea, and tobacco are cultivated. Teak, timber wood and forest wealth are produced in this zone.

Administrative_areas: Northern State, Rive Nile State, northern parts of North Darfur State & western parts of Red Sea State. In addition to Gadarif, Blue Nile, Upper Nile, White Nile, Sinnar & Southern Kordofan States
Agricultural_practices: Direct planting, transplanting and propagate vegetatively some fruit crops, broadcasting and drilling field crops. Wheat and Faba been cultivated by the floods in Hud es-Sileim. Datepalm fruit planed in the Nile banks. Commercial rainfed semi-mechanized farming production is practised, mainly sorghum plantation followed by sesame, groundnut and hibiscus (Karkade)

Administrative_areas: Most of Sudan, mainly in Kordofan, Darfur, White Nile & Blue Nile. North parts of Gadarif, Southern parts of Kassala & Kordofan containing Qash, Abu Habbil and Tokar Deltas. Southern parts of Kordofan, Southern parts of Gadarif & Southern parts of Souther
Agricultural_practices: Traditional rainfed farming subsistence production is practised, mainly sorghum, millet and limited areas under horticultural crops. Traditional rainfed is practised mainly sorghum and sesame. Irrigated Truck-Production is mainly practised in which cotton, groundnut and wheat is cultivated. Mainly Truck-Production is practised for sorghum, it is semi-mechanized, and illicit wood cut is practised affecting badly the forests.

Mainly Truck-Production is practised for sorghum, it is semi-mechanized, and illicit wood cut is practised affecting badly the forests.

Administrative_areas: Found only in the Northern region in the Districts of Tonkolili, Bombali, Port Loko and Kambia Plateaux areas and saucer-shaped and temporarily flooded in the rains, could be found in the range of 100-200 m above sea level.
Agricultural_practices: Rice farming, vegetables in dry season, sweet potato and cassava in dry season, seasonal fishing in wet season, cattle rearing in dry season.

Administrative_areas: Available in valleys of all the land formations except the coastal plains where we have Mangroves. They range from 50-1900 meters above sea level.
Agricultural_practices: Swamp rice farming, vegetable farming in dry season, groundnuts in dry season, sweetpotato and cassava farming in dry season, inland fishing

Administrative_areas: In the Coastal Plains, most of it is swampy, covers 15% of country, averages 50km in width and does not rise above 50m, mainly in the South and South West and North-West of the country.
Agricultural_practices: Rice farming, fishing including oysters, and fire wood cutting. Piassava retting.

Administrative_areas: Found along the banks of the major rivers that empty into the Ocean in the Bonthe and Pujehun Districts. They lie below 50 m above sea level.
Agricultural_practices: Rice farming, fishing, produce transportation and vegetable production.

Administrative_areas: Comprises Fatick, Kaolack and Diourbel regions, Mbour Division and an important part of Thiès, Tivaouane, Kébémer and Louga Divisions.
Agricultural_practices: As noted from its name, this zone is dominated by groundnut cultivation, in alternation with rainfed millet (les than 1% of the land is irrigated). Agricultural practices are characterized by the disappearance of fallows due to the high human pressure on land and the absence of policy to maintain soil fertility. This explains the multiple factors of land deterioration, amplified by extensive livestock activities that consume the few plants found and protected areas dominated by species of Combretaceae and Mimosaceae (mostly Faidherbia albida).

Administrative_areas: Comprises Kolda and Ziguinchor administrative Regions.
Agricultural_practices: This zone is very favourable for agricultural activities because of its precipitation, and the migrants from Arachidier basin and even east Senegal come in for agricultural purposes. The main activities are upland rice and cotton cultivation, traditional fishing in rivers and extensive livestock activities.

Administrative_areas: Comprises Bakel Division and Tambacounda administrative Region. The lowest population density of Senegal is found here (8 inhabitants/km2).
Agricultural_practices: Agricultural activities are variable. The low population density in this zone has enabled movements of people from other populated zones for extensive agriculture purposes and transhumant animal rearing with its associated problems on grazing. Inland fishing is also practiced in rivers Falémé, Gambia and Niokolo. Lumbering is carried out in unclassified domain, with yearly quotas of 500 000 quintals of coal and 60 000 m3 of wood. The presence of Niokolo-Koba national park and important animal reserves are favourable for the tourism. The zone has potential for mining. The exploitation of the mining resources shall include environmental risks, that add to the existing problems such as bush fires, overgrazing, deforestation and water erosion.

Inland fishing is also practiced in rivers Falémé, Gambia and Niokolo. Lumbering is carried out in unclassified domain, with yearly quotas of 500 000 quintals of coal and 60 000 m3 of wood. The presence of Niokolo-Koba national park and important animal reserves are favourable for the tourism. The zone has potential for mining. The exploitation of the mining resources shall include environmental risks, that add to the existing problems such as bush fires, overgrazing, deforestation and water erosion.

Scientific_name: Cucurbita pepo L. subsp. pepo group Zucchini

Administrative_areas: Comprises the Region of Dakar, and the Atlantic coast of the Regions of Thiès, Louga and Saint-Louis.
Agricultural_practices: About 80% of the horticultural production of the country is provided by this zone, only about 7% of the land is irrigated. There is intensive rearing (bovine and poultry). However, pressure on water resources and land combined with low rainfall leads to progressive land salinity and sandiness following vegetation degradation and progressive dune threats.

Agricultural_practices: About 80% of the horticultural production of the country is provided by this zone, only about 7% of the land is irrigated. There is intensive rearing (bovine and poultry). However, pressure on water resources and land combined with low rainfall leads to progressive land salinity and sandiness following vegetation degradation and progressive dune threats.
Scientific_name: Cucurbita pepo L. subsp. pepo group Zucchini

Administrative_areas: Comprises far north parts of the Dagana, Podor, Matam and Bakel administrative Divisions.
Agricultural_practices: Rice cultivation, irrigated vegetable production and subsidence cropping are practiced in the Walo (zone closed to water sources). The main subsidence crops are sorghum and maize that are grown on flood lands of the Walo, after the withdrawal of river waters following the annual rise in the water level occurring in rainy season. Rainfed crops such as millet, groundnut, tropical-type vegetables, etc. are cultivated Diéri. There is artisan fishing in rivers, lake Guiers and their different branching as well as the extensive livestock in Diéri. The development of rice cultivation and intensive deforestation have led to problems of chemical degradation of waters, wind and water erosion as well as salinization and alkalinization of soils in this zone.

Administrative_areas: The regions covered are La Marie , Plaine Sophie, Chamarel, St Pierre, Henrietta, La Brasserie, Nouvelle France, Highlands.
Agricultural_practices: Major crops grown are onion, potato, crucifers, carrots and green vegetables. Due to the cool climate specific crops are grown and creepers are limited to cucumber and pumpkin. Tea plantations were predominant in the early 80s and were partly removed and replaced by sugar cane plantation in the late 90s.

Administrative_areas: The regions covered are Plaisance, Beau Champ, Mon Choisy, Belle Mare, Medine, Bel Ombre
Agricultural_practices: Major vegetables crops grown are onion, Brinjal, creepers, tomato, chillies. Sugar cane plantation are mostly found in the marginal lands which are being abondoned in the actual context. Most of the irrigation projects are found in these regions, plots of state land are being parcelled into settlements  of defined size and leased to Agricultural Cooperatives. The irrigation system used are mainly overhead sprinkler. Pineapple has been cultivated in particular regions over large extent.

Administrative_areas: Comprises the  wilayas (Regions) of Tiris Zemmour, Adrar, Inchiri and Tagant, the Moughataa of Boumdeïd (Assaba), Tamchakett (Hodh El Gharbi) and Oulata (Hodh Echarghui)
Agricultural_practices: Oasis-type agriculture: date palm dominated with sub stages of fruit trees, cereals (wheat, oat), vegetables (carrot, tomato, cabbage and forage (alfalfa). Sometimes recessional crops are found around oases and behind dams on limono sandy soils.

Administrative_areas: Comprises the District of Nouakchott, the wilaya (Region) of Dakhelet Nouadhibou. More than a quarter of the Mauritanian population lives in this zone.
Agricultural_practices: Vegetable cropping and dairy animal rearing (cows, camels) are dominant activities of this zone. Vegetable production is decreasing because of the abandonment of the irrigation by the waste water of processing industries; the competition of imports (Morocco, Senegal) and the national production from other agro-ecological zones of the country.

Administrative_areas: Comprises the south of 4 wilayas (Regions): Trarza (the Moughataa of Boghé, Bababé and M'Bagne),  Gorgol (the Moughataa of Kaédi and Maghama),  Guidimakha (the Moughataa of Sélibaby)
Agricultural_practices: Agriculture: dominant. Rainfed and subsidence crops: sorghum, millet, maize, cowpea, groundnut, watermelon, etc). Irrigated crops: rice, maize, sorghum, vegetables, fruit trees. Cultural techniques: dominated by manual practices. Riziculture: manual in Upper River (Brakna, Gorgol, Guidimakha), semi mechanized in lower River (Trarza for land preparation and harvesting). Use of herbicides: frequent.

Administrative_areas: Comprises 3 wilayas (Regions): Assaba, 2 Hodhs without Moughataa (Divisions), Ould Yengé (Guidimakha), Mbout and Monguel (Gorgol), Aleg and Magta-Lahjar (Brakna), Mederdra and R'Kiz (Trarza).
Agricultural_practices: Rainfed crops and crops grown under dam (sorghum, millet, maize, cowpea). Mixed cropping is common and fertilizer use is rare. Use of animal traction: rare. Use of manure: frequent. Cultural operations: manual. Crop protection: seed treatments with fungicides. Use of improved varieties: rare. Vegetable cropping: developed by women cooperatives.

Administrative_areas: It is an extension of the lowlands in the south eastern part of the country, Quthing to Qachas Nek along the Senqu River and its tributary valleys covering 8% of the land area and even parts of Thaba-Tseka have similar conditions.
Agricultural_practices: Crops (summer and winter), fodder crops. Mixed farming, intensive and commercial more than in other zones. Summer crops: maize, sorghum, potatoes, sunflower. Winter: wheat, peas. Pumped sprinkler irrigation. Sorghum thrives well in this zone due to its better drought tolerance than maize.

Agricultural_practices: Rainfed cropping on forest land (burnt land), in plains and in low lands; high soil occupation; irrigation from starts December for 3 to 4 months only. Short dry season. Rotation rice, groundnut, maize, cassava in small hills and rice, vegetables in low lands; mixed cropping groundnut-maize, maize-cowpea, rice-maize, plantain-food crops and plantain-fruit crops. Control of weeds, pests and diseases.

Administrative_areas: Konkouré, Wouré Kaba, Soya, Boulywel, Tolo, Timbo, Saramoussaya, Poredaka, Bouriya, Gongorè, Gnagara, Kegneko (Mamou); Koba, Mity, Ditinn, Boyé, Kanka Labé, Kebaly (Dalaba); Brouwal Tapè, Bantignèl, Massi, Sangaréah, Leymirou, Dongöl Touma, Ningué Landè,
Agricultural_practices: The agrarian system combines very intensive cropping zones in the tapades and the extensive zones in the periphery. Animal rearing is associated with agriculture. Rainfed cultivation on burnt land is practiced after a short fallow. Intensive cultivation of vegetables and potato in pluvial and under irrigation in dry season. Mixed cropping of cassava, taro, sweetpotato, gourd and vegetables in the tapades. Control of animal digression, weeds, pests and diseases is common.

Agricultural_practices: Rainfed crops with slash and burn type of agriculture (dominant in the north), in plain and lowland. Irrigation starting from late November for non seasonal crops, especially for vegetable crops (dominant in the south). Crops rotation of rice/groundnut/cassava and fonio; rice/vegetable - maize/groundnut. Association of rice-sorghum and groundnut-maize. Fight against weeds, rodents, birds and treatment against diseases and insects.

Control of iron toxicity, weeds, pests and diseases.

Administrative_areas: Estuary province
Agricultural_practices: Conventional market gardening. The methods used are more modern with applications of fertilizers, chemical pesticides and irrigation for farmers with large farms. There is no mastery of appropriate cultural techniques in the applications of these technologies. Crop rotation is practiced in some zones, while in others, pure cropping is practice. Food crops: population density is very high in the Estuary zone (50-60 % of national population), pressure on land is high and this reduces the fallow period. Food crop are generally cultivated on burnt land after a fallow of 5 to 7 years. Pests and diseases are not controlled by any recommended method. Farmers do not control plant parasites except in situation of severe infestations that they request assistance form competent bodies.

Food crops: population density is very high in the Estuary zone (50-60 % of national population), pressure on land is high and this reduces the fallow period. Food crop are generally cultivated on burnt land after a fallow of 5 to 7 years. Pests and diseases are not controlled by any recommended method. Farmers do not control plant parasites except in situation of severe infestations that they request assistance form competent bodies.

Agroecological_zones: Oyem, Bitam, Minvoul, Mitzic and Médouneu
Administrative_areas: Woleu Ntem province
Agricultural_practices: Conventional market gardening. The methods used are more modern with applications of fertilizers, chemical pesticides and irrigation for farmers with large farms. There is no mastery of appropriate cultural techniques in the applications of these technologies. Crop rotation is practiced in some zones, while in others, pure cropping is practice. Food crops: Population density is not very high in the Woleu N'tem zone, and there is no problem with land availability. Food crop are generally cultivated on burnt land after a fallow of 8 to 12 years. As in the Estuary province, pests and diseases are not controlled by any recommended method. Farmers do not control plant parasites except in situation of severe infestations that they request assistance form competent bodies.

Agricultural_practices: Conventional market gardening. The methods used are more modern with applications of fertilizers, chemical pesticides and irrigation for farmers with large farms. There is no mastery of appropriate cultural techniques in the applications of these technologies. Crop rotation is practiced in some zones, while in others, pure cropping is practice. Food crops: Population density is not very high in the Woleu N'tem zone, and there is no problem with land availability. Food crop are generally cultivated on burnt land after a fallow of 8 to 12 years. As in the Estuary province, pests and diseases are not controlled by any recommended method. Farmers do not control plant parasites except in situation of severe infestations that they request assistance form competent bodies.

Administrative_areas: Lagunes, South Comoé, Lower Sassandra, Upper Sassandra, South Bandama and Mountain Regions
Agricultural_practices: Oil crops: oil palm, coconut; Cereals: maize; roots and tubers: yam, cassava; vegetables and legume crops. Other crops: banana, plantain, cocoa, coffee; rubber, banana, pineapple. Food crops are generally associated together or with perennial crops in the first years. Cropping system is cassava-based and/or upland rice in the west.
